p2
VConcert to please the soul
p3
sVnews
p4
VGayatri Venkataraghavan, endowed with good stage presence, has a clear and well trained soft voice enabling her to reveal the best of her musical skills with soothing effect. South Indian C ltural Association arranged her concert on Monday, timing it with its Foundation Day celebrations held at Ravindra Bharati. Gayatri's approach to the concert was traditional and she set her repertoire in the same mould, mixing with some rare numbers. Her sensitive manodharma was revealed in the way she structured her raga essays and swarakalpana a with sense of proportion that contributed to framing her lively concert.She breathed freshness in the rendition of kirtanas, stressing more on lyrical beauty. Gayatri began learning music from Padma Veeraraghavan at an early age and later from Sundaresan. Presently she is under the tutelage of P.S.Narayanaswamy. After chanting of a sloka on Ganesha, Gayatri launched her concert with a traditional opening with Nata raga varnam. This was followed by a rare number of Thyagaraja Tarama Nee Mahima Pogada in Kalyani, he wrote on Lord Venkateswara in his sojourn to Tirupati. Later she rendered a Tamil composition of Papanasam Sivan &#8216;Kumaran Tai' in Yadukulakamboji.
